The proof proceeds by computing the distribution of $i \in X$ (which is a random variable on `Prop`).
We have `map (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun S ↦ i ∈ S) (map X P)`.
Since `map X P = Ber(u, p)`, we use the definition `bernoulliOn_eq_map` to express `Ber(u, p)` as the image of the product measure `infinitePi ...` under the map `fun p ↦ {k | p k}`.
Composing the maps, `(fun S ↦ i ∈ S) ∘ (fun p ↦ {k | p k})` simplifies to the projection `fun p ↦ p i`.
The pushforward of the product measure `infinitePi μ` by the projection `eval i` is the component measure `μ i` (by `map_eval_infinitePi`).
For $i \in u$, `μ i = p • δ_{True} + (1-p) • δ_{False}`.
The same holds for $j \in u$, so the distributions are equal.

