Consider the proof of `IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem`.
The goal is to show that the distributions of `i ∈ X` and `j ∈ X` are identical.
We have `hX : map X P = Ber(u, p)`.
The distribution of `i ∈ X` is `map (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P`.
Using the composition rule for measures, `map (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P = map (fun s ↦ i ∈ s) (map X P)`.
Substituting `map X P` with `Ber(u, p)` (using `hX`), we get `map (fun s ↦ i ∈ s) Ber(u, p)`.
Using `bernoulliOn_eq_map`, `Ber(u, p)` is the pushforward of `infinitePi μ` under `fun p ↦ {k | p k}`.
Thus, the distribution is `map (fun s ↦ i ∈ s) (map (fun p ↦ {k | p k}) (infinitePi μ))`.
Composing the maps, we get `map (fun p ↦ i ∈ {k | p k}) (infinitePi μ)`.
Since `i ∈ {k | p k}` is `p i`, this is `map (fun p ↦ p i) (infinitePi μ)`.
By the property of product measures (or projective limits), the marginal `map (fun p ↦ p i) (infinitePi μ)` is simply the component measure `μ i`.
For `bernoulliOn`, `μ i = toNNReal p • dirac (i ∈ u) + ...`.
Since `i ∈ u` and `j ∈ u`, `μ i` and `μ j` are both `p • dirac True + (1-p) • dirac False`.
Thus the distributions are equal.

